# Personal Wishlist Manager

A WordPress plugin for keeping a personal wishlist inside your own site, with a clean admin workflow, a browsable frontend grid, and a quick-add bookmarklet for saving items from around the web.

## Release Info

- Current version: `1.0.7`
- Requires WordPress: `6.0+`
- Requires PHP: `7.4+`
- License: `GPLv2 or later`

## What This Plugin Does

Personal Wishlist Manager gives you a simple way to collect items you want, organize them, and publish them on a WordPress page.

You can:

- add wishlist items manually from the WordPress admin
- save items from other websites with the Browser Quick Add bookmarklet
- organize items by category
- store price, product link, image, and personal notes
- show the wishlist on your site with a shortcode or Gutenberg block
- let visitors browse with filters for search, category, price, and sort order

## Best For

- personal wishlists
- gift ideas
- collecting products for later
- visual inspiration boards
- hobby or collection tracking
- creators who want a public wishlist page on their own website

## Quick Start

1. Install and activate the plugin.
2. In WordPress admin, go to `Wishlist > Add New`.
3. Add your first item with a title, category, price, image, and product URL.
4. Create or edit a page where you want the wishlist to appear.
5. Add either:

```text
[personal_wishlist]
```

or the `Personal Wishlist` Gutenberg block.

## How To Use It

### Add Items Manually

Go to `Wishlist > Add New`.

For each item, you can enter:

- title
- category
- image URL
- product URL
- price
- reason or notes

This is the best option when you want full control over the details before publishing.

### Use Browser Quick Add

On the `Add New Wishlist Item` screen, there is a `Browser Quick Add` panel in the right sidebar.

Use it like this:

1. Drag the `Quick Add to Wishlist` button to your browser bookmarks bar.
2. Visit a product page on another website.
3. Click the bookmarklet.
4. Review the captured item details.
5. Edit anything you want before saving.

Quick Add can capture:

- page title
- product URL
- candidate product images
- price when detectable

The quick-add flow saves the chosen image into your WordPress Media Library instead of hotlinking the source image.

## Displaying The Wishlist

### Option 1: Shortcode

Use the shortcode on any page or post:

```text
[personal_wishlist]
```

### Option 2: Gutenberg Block

In the block editor:

1. Add the `Personal Wishlist` block.
2. Configure categories, sort order, columns, filters, and item limit in the block sidebar.
3. Use the live preview in the editor to check the layout.

## Common Shortcode Examples

### Default wishlist

```text
[personal_wishlist]
```

### Four-column layout

```text
[personal_wishlist columns="4"]
```

### Show only one category

```text
[personal_wishlist category="Books"]
```

### Limit the list

```text
[personal_wishlist limit="12"]
```

### Hide filters

```text
[personal_wishlist show_filters="false"]
```

## Shortcode Reference

- `columns`: `1` to `4`
- `category`: show one category
- `categories`: show multiple categories
- `sort`: `alphabetical`, `price_asc`, `price_desc`, `date_desc`, `date_asc`
- `limit`: maximum number of items
- `user_id`: target user ID
- `show_filters`: `true` or `false`
- `show_search`: `true` or `false`
- `show_category`: `true` or `false`
- `show_price`: `true` or `false`
- `show_sort`: `true` or `false`

Default sort is `date_desc`, which means newest items first.

## Admin Areas

### Wishlist

The main admin list where you can:

- browse all items
- search items
- edit existing items
- delete items
- bulk delete items

### Add New

The form for creating a wishlist item manually. This is also where the Browser Quick Add tools live.

### Categories

Shows the categories currently used in your wishlist so you can understand how your list is grouped.

### Settings

Settings are split into sections for:

- display options
- shortcode generator
- advanced settings
- import/export tools

## Display Features

The frontend wishlist supports:

- responsive grid layouts
- search
- category filtering
- price range filtering
- sorting
- inline reset for filters when filters are active
- mobile-friendly filter behavior

## Data Stored For Each Item

Each wishlist item can include:

- title
- category
- image URL
- product URL
- price
- notes or reason
- created date
- updated date

## Import And Export

You can export your wishlist from `Wishlist > Settings > Import/Export`.

Available formats:

- CSV
- JSON

This is useful for backups, migrations, and personal record keeping.

## Appearance And Customization

The plugin includes built-in frontend styling, but you can also customize it.

Available options include:

- default number of columns
- default sort order
- currency symbol
- currency position
- custom CSS

## Recent Improvements In 1.0.7

- refined the wishlist filter UX so the controls themselves represent current filter state
- removed the separate active filter indicator row
- added an inline reset control that appears only when filters are active
- improved browsing clarity with a stronger results header and cleaner card hierarchy
- improved Gutenberg block live preview styling in the editor
- removed image lazy loading to avoid flashing while browsing

## FAQ

### Do I need to know code to use this plugin?

No. You can manage items entirely from the WordPress admin and use either a shortcode or block to display the wishlist.

### Can I use the block editor instead of a shortcode?

Yes. The plugin supports both.

### Can I save products from other websites?

Yes. Use the Browser Quick Add bookmarklet from the `Add New` screen.

### Can I customize the design?

Yes. You can use the built-in settings and add custom CSS.

### Is this meant for multiple users?

Right now it is primarily structured as a personal wishlist manager for a single site owner/admin workflow.

## File Structure

- `personal-wishlist-manager.php`: main plugin bootstrap
- `includes/`: core PHP logic
- `admin/`: admin screens and scripts
- `templates/`: frontend output templates
- `public/`: frontend CSS, JS, and images
- `blocks/`: Gutenberg block files

## Privacy

This plugin does not send wishlist data to an external service by default.

Wishlist data is stored in your WordPress database.

## Support Notes

If you are testing changes locally, the main things to verify are:

1. adding and editing wishlist items in wp-admin
2. viewing the wishlist via shortcode or block
3. filtering on desktop and mobile
4. Browser Quick Add saving correctly
5. block preview rendering correctly in the editor

